üìù Step 2: Creating the Submission Form and Database Connection
This step is crucial as it involves the basic Create operation (from CRUD) and establishes the connection between your web page and the database.

Part 1: Setup Your Project Folder
Locate XAMPP: Navigate to the XAMPP installation directory.

Go to htdocs: Inside the XAMPP folder, find the htdocs folder. This is where Apache looks for all your web projects.

Create Project Folder: Inside htdocs, create a new folder for our project and name it doctrack_project.

Create Files: Inside the doctrack_project folder, create three new files using your VS Code editor:

index.php (Our main form page)

config.php (To store database connection settings)

style.css (For custom styling, though Bootstrap will do most of the work)

Folder Structure Check:

XAMPP/htdocs/doctrack_project/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ index.php
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ config.php
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ style.css
Part 2: The Database Connection (config.php)
We need a separate file to hold the database credentials. This makes your code cleaner and easier to update.

Open config.php and add the following code:

PHP

<?php
// Database credentials (change if you used a different database name or password)
define('DB_SERVER', 'localhost');
define('DB_USERNAME', 'root');
define('DB_PASSWORD', ''); // XAMPP default is usually no password
define('DB_NAME', 'doctrack');

// Attempt to connect to MySQL database
$conn = mysqli_connect(DB_SERVER, DB_USERNAME, DB_PASSWORD, DB_NAME);

// Check connection
if($conn === false){
    die("ERROR: Could not connect. " . mysqli_connect_error());
}
?>
What this does: It defines the necessary connection variables and then uses the mysqli_connect() function to attempt a connection. If it fails, it stops the program and shows an error.

