C. PHP Processing (Insert this inside the opening PHP tag at the top of index.php)
This PHP code runs when the form is submitted (POST method).

PHP

// Processing form data when form is submitted
if($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST"){

    // 1. Collect and sanitize input data
    $doc_name = trim($_POST["doc_name"]);
    $owner_name = trim($_POST["owner_name"]);
    $status = trim($_POST["status"]);
    $date_event = trim($_POST["date_event"]);
    $location = trim($_POST["location"]);
    $contact = trim($_POST["contact"]);
    
    // 2. Prepare an INSERT statement
    $sql = "INSERT INTO documents (doc_name, owner_name, status, date_event, location, contact) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)";
         
    if($stmt = mysqli_prepare($conn, $sql)){
        // Bind variables to the prepared statement as parameters
        mysqli_stmt_bind_param($stmt, "ssssss", $param_doc_name, $param_owner_name, $param_status, $param_date_event, $param_location, $param_contact);
        
        // Set parameters
        $param_doc_name = $doc_name;
        $param_owner_name = $owner_name;
        $param_status = $status;
        $param_date_event = $date_event;
        $param_location = $location;
        $param_contact = $contact;
        
        // 3. Attempt to execute the prepared statement
        if(mysqli_stmt_execute($stmt)){
            $message = "Report submitted successfully! Thank you.";
            // Clear inputs after successful submission
            $doc_name = $owner_name = $status = $date_event = $location = $contact = "";
        } else{
            $message = "ERROR: Could not submit report. " . mysqli_error($conn);
        }

        // Close statement
        mysqli_stmt_close($stmt);
    }
    
    // Close connection
    mysqli_close($conn);
}
What this does: This uses Prepared Statements (the mysqli_prepare and mysqli_stmt_bind_param functions) which is a security best practice for preventing SQL Injection attacks. It takes the form data and safely inserts it into the documents table.

‚úÖ Test Your Code
Make sure XAMPP (Apache and MySQL) is still running.

Open your browser and go to: http://localhost/doctrack_project/index.php

Fill out the form completely and click Submit Report.

If successful, you should see the message: "Report submitted successfully! Thank you."

Verify: Go back to phpMyAdmin (http://localhost/phpmyadmin/), click on the doctrack database, click on the documents table, and then click the Browse tab. You should see your submitted data there.

Please confirm that you have successfully submitted and viewed at least one document report in your database.

